==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Swath
<hw>Swath</hw> <pr>(sw⟦add⟧th; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>swa⟦edh⟧u</ets> a track, trace; akin to D. <ets>zwaad</ets>,
<ets>zwad</ets>, <ets>zwade</ets>, a swath of grass, G.
<ets>schwad</ets>, <ets>schwaden</ets>; perhaps, originally, a shred.
Cf. <er>Swathe</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A line of
grass or grain cut and thrown together by the scythe in mowing or
cradling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The whole sweep of a scythe, or the whole breadth
from which grass or grain is cut by a scythe or a machine, in mowing or
cradling; <as>as, to cut a wide <ex>swath</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A band or fillet; a swathe.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Swath bank</b></col>, <cd>a row of new-mown grass.</cd>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swathe</ent>⟦br⟧
